10年","1587":"1587年","1598":"1598年","1585":"1585年","Abt 1545":"大約1545年","1493":"1493年","1490":"1490年","1549":"1549年","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"英國坎布利其爾蕾托 艾福斯達","England":"英國","lifeSummary":"Frederica Smith於1493年出生在英國。她於1510年與Joseph Grundy在英國結婚。他們至少是1個女兒的父母。"},"zh-hans":{"1493–":"1493年–殁","1490–Male":"1490年–殁","1545–1598":"1545年–1598年","1493–Female":"1493年–殁","1569":"1569年","1558":"1558年","1545":"1545年","1510":"1510年","1587":"1587年","1598":"1598年","1585":"1585年","Abt 1545":"大约1545年","1493":"1493年","1490":"1490年","1549":"1549年","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"英国坎布利其爾蕾托 艾福斯達","England":"英国","lifeSummary":"Frederica Smith于1493年出生在英国。她于1510年与Joseph Grundy在英国结婚。他们至少是1个女儿的父母。"},"hr":{"1493–":"1493.–preminula","1490–Male":"1490–preminuo","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493.–preminula","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510.","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"oko 1545.","1493":"1493.","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"cs":{"1493–":"1493–Zesnulá","1490–Male":"1490–Zesnulý","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Zesnulá","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"okolo 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"1493–":"1493–Afdød","1490–Male":"1490–Afdød","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Afdød","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"omkring 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"1493–":"1493–Overleden","1490–Male":"1490–Overleden","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"circa 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1493–":"1493–Deceased","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"about 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]},{"name":"Frederica","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Frederick ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":56,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":65,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":76,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":92,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":94,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Frederica Smith was born in 1493, in England. She married Joseph Grundy in 1510, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1493–":"1493–Surnud","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"umbes 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1493–":"1493–Kuollut","1490–Male":"1490–Kuollut","1545–1598":"1545–1598","1493–Female":"1493–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1585":"1585","Abt 1545":"noin 1545","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Eversden, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1493–":"1493–Décédée","1490–M